    "The identification of several papers from the same research group (DemRQ3) shows the ongoing efforts and technological developments rather than a paper resulting from a one-off, isolated study.",
    "We found only one case in our analysis.",
    "The University of Oxford released the BEHRT model in 2020 (Li et al. 2020) and advanced this model in two works published in 2022 (Rao et al. 2022a, b) and another in 2023 (Li et al. 2023a, b).",
    "The Graduate Institute of Biomedical Electronics and Bioinformatics at the National Taiwan University used transformer models for two disease pattern retrieval and classification in 2021 (Boursalie et al. 2021) and prediction of postoperative mortality in 2022 (Chen et al. 2022).",
    "However, our analysis did not consider this latter application since it does not use longitudinal data."
